"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111202","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-18","<p>Highways England entered into a conditional contract with BP for the sale of Tollgate Hotel which was conditional on planning permission being granted for development. The planning applications submitted have been subject to a number of judicial reviews, which has delayed the sale. As a result, Highways England have now agreed with BP to move to an unconditional contract, which means the sale will no longer be dependent on gaining planning permission and Highways England will now be able to progress the sale.</p><p><em> </em></p><p>Given that Highways England will be entering into a new unconditional contract with BP for the sale of the property, they have no plans to remarket at this time.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-04-18T11:01:35.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111202/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111202/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-04-10","A2: Garages and Petrol Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the proposed sale of Tollgate Hotel Watling Street Gravesend Kent DA13 9RA to BP Oil UK Limited, what information his Department holds on proposals to re-market the property for sale as a result of the seven-year delay in BP securing planning on that site.","false","Biography information for Adam Holloway","Gravesham","Adam Holloway","243372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111203","Home Office","false","2019-06-07","<p>We have checked the records that the department has kept since the introduction of the Cabinet Office guidance on settlement agreements on 1 February 2015 and confirm that we have one record, of using an NDA with a departmental staff member in July 2015.</p><p>The use of this NDA was unintentional i.e. the standard NDA paragraph was accidently left in the template by mistake. We are not aware of the Home Office using NDA for departmental staff other than this since the new guidance was introduced. However, the records examined were cross-matched from several different data sets, assembled for different purposes. As there were some gaps in the data sets, while we are confident this was the only instance, we cannot guarantee that we were able to identify every case.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-06-07T16:22:23.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111203/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111203/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-04-10","Home Office: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many non-disclosure agreements his Department has entered into with departmental staff in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","243415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111204","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-04-15","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) strongly believes that no-one should be homeless, least of all someone who has served their country. However, there is no substantive evidence to suggest that veterans are over-represented in the homeless population. As part of the recently launched Veterans Strategy the Government has made clear its commitment to tackling rough sleeping and homelessness and ensuring that all veterans have a secure place to live.</p><p>We recognise that there are limited statistics on homelessness; that is the why the MOD and the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government are working together to gather more comprehensive data on this issue. The Combined Homelessness and Information Network statistics suggest that 3% of the rough sleeping population in London have served in the Armed Forces and other independent research shows that the rough sleeping figures for veterans are around 3-4% across the UK. The same research shows that that an individual is less likely to be homeless if they have served in the Armed Forces.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2019-04-15T15:32:51.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111204/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111204/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-04-10","Veterans: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will fund research into the number of former members of the armed forces who are homeless; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","243310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111205","Home Office","false","2019-04-24","<p>It is the responsibility of the police to investigate allegations of domestic abuse.</p><p>HMICFRS’ latest inspection on domestic abuse found that the police response continues to improve, particularly around the first response. Furthermore, police recorded domestic abuse crimes have increased by over 60% in the last three years, demonstrating increased victim confidence to report and better police recording of these crimes. Overall, prosecutions and convictions for domestic abuse are both up since 2010 – by 20 per cent and 28 per cent respectively, with 76% of all prosecutions resulting in successful convictions, the highest since 2010.</p><p><br>Our landmark draft Domestic Abuse Bill and consultation response published in January includes measures to help the police tackle domestic abuse, including the creation of a Domestic Abuse Protection Notice and Order and training for police. We will continue to monitor the police response through the Home Secretary chaired National Oversight Group and through HMICFRS inspections.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-04-24T13:06:21.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111205/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111205/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-04-10","Domestic Abuse: Criminal Investigation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans he has to establish a dedicated unit to investigate historic domestic abuse.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","243523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111206","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-04-16","<p>I refer my Hon Friend to the answer of 11 March 2109 to Question UIN 228010.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2019-04-16T13:39:08.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111206/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111206/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-04-10","High Rise Flats: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant of the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government of 28 January 2019, Official Report, column 465, on Leaseholders: Removal of Dangerous Materials, if he will publish the names of the 80 buildings where owners and developers have made a commitment to fund the cost of remediation, or have had a warrantee claim accepted.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","243416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111207","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-18","<p>There are no current plans to provide guidance of this nature. Management of rights of way, including footpaths, rests with the relevant local authority. The expectation is for local authorities, whenever possible, to look at the needs of all users including cyclists.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-04-18T09:11:58.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111207/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111207/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-04-10","Public Footpaths: Bicycles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if his Department will provide guidance on the rights of cyclists to walk a bicycle along a public footpath.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","243417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111208","Cabinet Office","false","2019-04-15","<p>The consultation Protecting the Debate: Intimidation, Influence and Information was launched last year. We are currently reviewing the responses and we will issue a response in due course.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2019-04-15T13:23:00.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111208/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1111208/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-04-10","Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans his Department has to publish a response to the consultation entitled Protecting the Debate: Intimidation, Influence and Information.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","243418"
